<i>A small mind is a tidy mind</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uchronomis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chronomis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(12/4/01 6:54:23 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: No slacking!</span><hr size=1> Regens are nice, but they're mostly for sticking on necros so they can regenerate mana without requiring as many heals.  The same is true of using a regen on a shaman, of course, but they provide their own regeneration.<br>
<br>
The problem with using regen on other people in a raid is that the effect is negated by cleric's complete healing.  The regen took up a buff slot, but the fifty or a hundred or two hundred hit points it regenerated between complete heals was fairly meaningless given the speed at which mobs dish out damage at the level you get the spell, and the cleric's complete heal tops off hit points completely, erasing both the effect and the effectiveness of the regen.<br>
<br>
Druid and shaman regenerations are too slow to be useful in raid situations, or even in 50+ experience groups.  What's needed is a fast regen similar to the cleric's Celestial Heal, which in my opinion should have gone to shammies and druids instead of clerics.  Prior to that spell being added, heals over time were the domain of druids and shamen, with clerics being masters of the direct heal.  The situation was similar to wizards being the masters of direct damage spells and necros of damage over time.  <br>
<br>
With clerics getting Celestial Heal, that changed.  Instead of us getting the fast regeneration we needed clerics got it, and now a raid-viable heal over time can probably never be given to us without treading on the cleric's sacred ground.  The new spell does nothing to change the situation-it's too slow by far, and the casting time limit negates what little utility it might have had.  I'll get it, when I attain the high level required for it, but it will go to the back of the book only to be fished out when there's a necro in the group.  <br>
<br>
Only if it can be bought from a vendor, by the way.  No way am I ever raiding some god in order to get the opportunity to roll on Nature's recovery.  If Verant wants me to fill my spellbook with junk like this, they can at least make it attainable.<br>
<br>
 - Chronomis<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uchronomis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chronomis</A> at: 12/4/01 7:01:29 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ulotusflystewnicely.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lotusfly Stewnicely</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(12/4/01 7:21:30 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.prexus.com/ef/becky/snap.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: No slacking!</span><hr size=1> On Vulak, Vyemm, and numerous other end-game fights to date, a lot of raid healing is done via regens.<br>
<br>
I usually put druids in charge of healing hybrids/casters, and usually give myself a rogue or two.  (Clerics being limited resources in my guild).  I'm a little bemused to hear that regenerations of various kinds don't work for you under these circumstances, most groups usually ask for regen a little before such fights, at least in my experience.  I'd rather have my guild's clerics CHing the main tank(s) than wasting mana on a rogue/hybrid/caster, who should be low enough agro to heal with regen (and fungal tunic, on the long fights)<br>
<br>
On a side note, I took to being the main healer in Sebilis recently, and primary healed in each camp (excepting Lower Zone Out and the Myconid King, of course) - saving the groups a huge amount of peridot money in the process, just to show that it could be done (and earning some respect and flattering remarks for the druid class in the process, hehe).  These are random pickup groups, sometimes with one or two guild friends in, but usually containing just medium-equipped low-mid 50s expers.  <br>
<br>
In these situations, regen was magnificent, of course.  With Nature's Recovery, my life would have been even easier there. ^_^<br>
<br>
As I say, if you'd rather not use it or hold out for a Celestial Heal... then that's your right!<br>
<br>
