<i>A small mind is a tidy mind</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uquelm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quelm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Wolf Elemental</span><br> <font color=#333399>(12/4/01 2:46:36 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: No slacking!</span><hr size=1> Well, we'll know soon enough, but I think the utility of Nature's Recovery depends on stacking.<br>
<br>
If it doesn't stack with Regrowth, and assuming you are keeping Regrowth of the Grove up on your group, Nature's Recovery provides 450 additional hps for 250 mana in 3 minutes.  (Regrowth heals 450 hitpoints in 3 minutes.)  The marginal healing provided by Recovery is worse than Chloroblast, which provides 385 hitpoints for 175 mana in less than a tick.<br>
<br>
In 15 minutes, you could heal 4560 hps with regrowth and 6 chloroblasts for 1350 mana.<br>
In 15 minutes, you could heal 4500 hps with nature's recovery for 1500 mana.  <b>Mana-efficient druids won't even use this spell if it is a replacement for regrowth.</b><br>
<br>
*If* it stacks with Regrowth then the comparison to Nature's Touch is fair.  If not, the only benefit is *slightly* faster healing - increasing our healing power by 150 hps on the main tank over the course of a one minute fight.<br>
<br>
I think regens are great heals.  I've healed groups in Sebilis and Howling Stones and had fun doing it.  Regrowth, Pack Chloro and help from my groupmates kept us killing quickly.  However, without stacking, *this* regen doesn't do much for me.<br>
<br>
-Quelm, 58 Preserver<br>
